<paragraph id="9150EA6AFFA3FFB3FF1DFF6CFC86BBDB" blockId="50.[151,1437,151,895]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">
<typeStatus id="4E5454C8FFA3FFB3FF1DFF6CFEB4BAD8" box="[199,303,151,175]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Holotype</typeStatus>
is an adult male, with medium long, simple penis, tapering towards tip and without defined papilla. The radula (
<figureCitation id="09D4F6EFFFA3FFB3FEC5FF47FE18BAA3" box="[287,387,188,212]" captionStart="FIGURE 30" captionStartId="51.[151,250,1129,1152]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,543,1110]" captionTargetId="figure-458@51.[151,1436,543,1116]" captionTargetPageId="51" captionText="FIGURE 30. Radulae. A. Belomitra brachymitra n. sp., holotype, dorsal view of the central part of radular membrane (shell see Fig. 29G–I). B. Belomitra hypsomitra n. sp., holotype, dorsal view of the central part of radular membrane (shell see Fig. 29A–C)." pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Fig. 30B</figureCitation>
) consists of approximately 80 rows of teeth, 7 nascent, and 10–11 anteriormost ones strongly damaged. Radula 
<quantity id="5617478FFFA3FFB3FEB9FF24FE53BA80" box="[355,456,223,247]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.44" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" unit="mm" value="1.44">1.44 mm</quantity>
long (0.19 AL), narrow, about 75 µm in width (1.02% of AL). Lateral teeth about 65 µm in maximum length (0.89% of AL), with narrow base, attached to the membrane at an angle of 7–12º to the longitudinal axis. Lateral teeth bicuspid, inner cusp more than twice as long as the outer one. Rachidian teeth closely spaced and cusps overlapping previous row; tooth base nearly triangular, with broader anterior edge which is hardly discernible from membrane; three closely spaced, rather delicate, cusps, central one twice as long as the lateral ones, emanating from posterior edge of tooth base.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D9F5B9E1FFA3FFB3FF1DFE4CFB70BBB8" box="[199,1259,439,464]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="9150EA6AFFA3FFB3FF1DFE4CFB70BBB8" blockId="50.[151,1437,151,895]" box="[199,1259,439,464]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis id="A39B3678FFA3FFB3FF1DFE4CFEF9BBA7" bold="true" box="[199,354,439,464]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Distribution:</emphasis>
Known from two stations off 
<collectingCountry id="E9F8AAFAFFA3FFB3FD6FFE4CFD44BBB8" box="[693,735,439,463]" name="Fiji" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Fiji</collectingCountry>
, alive in 
<quantity id="5617478FFFA3FFB3FC9EFE4CFC5EBBB8" box="[836,965,439,463]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.995" metricValueMax="4.07" metricValueMin="3.92" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" unit="m" value="399.5" valueMax="407.0" valueMin="392.0">392–407 m</quantity>
, shells to 
<quantity id="5617478FFFA3FFB3FBEEFE4CFBE0BBB8" box="[1076,1147,439,463]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.77" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" unit="m" value="477.0">477 m</quantity>
(
<figureCitation id="09D4F6EFFFA3FFB3FB50FE4CFB40BBA7" box="[1162,1243,439,464]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="36.[151,250,1360,1383]" captionTargetBox="[156,1430,451,1339]" captionTargetId="figure-430@36.[156,1431,451,1339]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURE 20. Distribution of Belomitra species. For Belomitra nesiotica and B. bouteti distribution areas and types localities are figured, not the individual collection sites. Type localities of B. brachymitra and B. hypsomitra off Fiji are marked with an arrow." pageId="50" pageNumber="51">
Fig. 
<emphasis id="A39B3678FFA3FFB3FB65FE4CFB40BBA7" bold="true" box="[1215,1243,439,464]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">20</emphasis>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D9F5B9E1FFA3FFB3FF1DFE27FE81B860" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="9150EA6AFFA3FFB3FF1DFE27FE81B860" blockId="50.[151,1437,151,895]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis id="A39B3678FFA3FFB3FF1DFE27FECABB83" bold="true" box="[199,337,476,500]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Etymology:</emphasis>
From the Greek 
<emphasis id="A39B3678FFA3FFB3FDC1FE27FDE0BB83" box="[539,635,476,500]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">hypselos</emphasis>
, meaning high, and suffix - 
<emphasis id="A39B3678FFA3FFB3FC67FE26FC62BB83" box="[957,1017,477,500]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">mitra</emphasis>
, by reference to the high, mitriform shell shape.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D9F5B9E1FFA3FFB3FF1DFDDFFA07B908" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="9150EA6AFFA3FFB3FF1DFDDFFC11B828" blockId="50.[151,1437,151,895]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis id="A39B3678FFA3FFB3FF1DFDDFFEA6B84B" bold="true" box="[199,317,548,572]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Remarks:</emphasis>
The other specimens of the species are very similar in shell outline, and differ only in having less pronounced knobs at the intersections of spiral cords and axial ribs.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9150EA6AFFA3FFB3FF1DFD97FE1FB898" blockId="50.[151,1437,151,895]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">
<taxonomicName id="56EF91E9FFA3FFB3FF1DFD97FE27B8F3" authorityName="Kantor &amp; Puillandre &amp; Rivasseau &amp; Bouchet" authorityYear="2012" box="[199,444,620,644]" class="Gastropoda" family="Belomitridae" genus="Belomitra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="hypsomitra">
<emphasis id="A39B3678FFA3FFB3FF1DFD97FE27B8F3" box="[199,444,620,644]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Belomitra hypsomitra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is most similar to 
<taxonomicName id="56EF91E9FFA3FFB3FD55FD96FCA3B8F3" authorityName="Kantor &amp; Puillandre &amp; Rivasseau &amp; Bouchet" authorityYear="2012" box="[655,824,620,644]" class="Gastropoda" family="Belomitridae" genus="Belomitra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="brachymitra">
<emphasis id="A39B3678FFA3FFB3FD55FD96FCA3B8F3" box="[655,824,620,644]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">B. brachymitra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The differences are discussed in the Remarks section of the latter species. 
<taxonomicName id="56EF91E9FFA3FFB3FEA7FD6AFD81B8DF" authorityName="Kantor &amp; Puillandre &amp; Rivasseau &amp; Bouchet" authorityYear="2012" box="[381,538,656,680]" class="Gastropoda" family="Belomitridae" genus="Belomitra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="hypsomitra">
<emphasis id="A39B3678FFA3FFB3FEA7FD6AFD81B8DF" box="[381,538,656,680]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">B. hypsomitra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
also has somewhat similar sculpture pattern to 
<taxonomicName id="56EF91E9FFA3FFB3FBF4FD6AFB03B8DF" box="[1070,1176,656,680]" class="Gastropoda" family="Belomitridae" genus="Belomitra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="radula">
<emphasis id="A39B3678FFA3FFB3FBF4FD6AFB03B8DF" box="[1070,1176,656,680]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">B. radula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but differs in having a more slender shell, a beaded shell surface, better pronounced columellar plaits, and in the nearly complete absence of a subsutural ramp.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9150EA6AFFA3FFB3FF1DFD07FDB8B92B" blockId="50.[151,1437,151,895]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">
Through its very slender shell, sculpture, and relatively well developed columellar plaits, 
<taxonomicName id="56EF91E9FFA3FFB3FAF6FD07FE8EB94F" authorityName="Kantor &amp; Puillandre &amp; Rivasseau &amp; Bouchet" authorityYear="2012" class="Gastropoda" family="Belomitridae" genus="Belomitra" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="hypsomitra">
<emphasis id="A39B3678FFA3FFB3FAF6FD07FE8EB94F" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Belomitra hypsomitra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
superficially resembles representatives of the family 
<taxonomicName id="56EF91E9FFA3FFB3FCAFFCE4FB8FB940" authorityName="MacDonald" authorityYear="1860" box="[885,1044,799,823]" class="Gastropoda" family="Costellariidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Mollusca" rank="family">Costellariidae</taxonomicName>
. Nevertheless the radula leaves no doubt about its taxonomic position.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9150EA6AFFA3FFB3FF1DFC9CFA07B908" blockId="50.[151,1437,151,895]" box="[199,1436,871,895]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">
Three of 
<specimenCount id="87E921E3FFA3FFB3FEF7FC9CFE4FB908" box="[301,468,871,895]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" type="generic">five specimens</specimenCount>
were drilled by an unknown predator, with up to 7 holes in the one shell (
<figureCitation id="09D4F6EFFFA3FFB3FAD7FC9CFA0AB908" box="[1293,1425,871,895]" captionStart="FIGURE 29" captionStartId="49.[151,250,1831,1854]" captionTargetBox="[188,1398,177,1810]" captionTargetId="figure-161@49.[188,1398,147,1810]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="FIGURE 29. A–F. Belomitra hypsomitra n. sp. A–C. Holotype, MNHN 24490, SL 18.7 mm (shell was drilled to extract the body) (radula see Fig. 30B). D. BORDAU 1, sta. DW1432, SL 10.7 mm, ventral view. E–F. BORDAU 1, sta. DW1432, SL 17.8 mm, shell drilled several times by the unknown predator. G–N. Belomitra brachymitra n. sp. G–I. Holotype, MNHN 24495, SL 9.5 mm (radula see Fig. 30A). J. SEM photograph of operculum of holotype. K. Paratype, BORDAU 1, sta. DW1486, SL 8.3 mm. L–M. Paratype, BORDAU 1, sta. DW1486, SL 10.9 mm (M is reproduced at the same scale as the shells of Belomitra hypsomitra for easier comparison). N. BORDAU 1, sta. DW1488, SL 13.2 mm. A–F, M, scale bar = 1 cm. G–I, K–L, N, scale bar = 5 mm." pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Fig. 29E–F</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
